l. 25. quorum, sqq. Translate, ‘Men whose cruelty is appeased neither by the death of the guilty nor the surrender of their liseless bodies, no nor by their possessions following their owner's surrender; men, I say, who know not how to be soothed till we have given them our very blood to suck and our bowels to tear.’

1. 26. corporum, in allusion to Brutulus Papius, the leader of the war-party in Samnium, who had made away with himself, in order that his fellow-citizens might be able to say that the author of the war had atoned for his offence. Niebuhr remarks that his act is one of the most heroic in all antiquity and outstrips Cato's similar deed.
